<subSubSection id="10ED9AC52D6AFF87FFC8FEE5FD410A9E" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="5848C94E2D6AFF87FFC8FEE5FD410A9E" blockId="2.[151,1436,151,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="6A83155C2D6AFF87FFC8FEE5FEE50A72" bold="true" box="[199,326,296,320]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Etymology</emphasis>
. This species is named in honor of the late writer John Updike. Although Updike published sparingly on Neotropical beetles (
<number id="EE3FDB692D6AFF87FEFBFE81FD930A56" box="[500,560,332,356]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1963.0">1963</number>
), his use of metaphors, widely admired by critics, recommends this honor because, in a sense, a species which mimics another is a kind of metaphor for the mimicked species and benefits by being confused for its model by uncritical predators.
</paragraph>
